lexUnit.name: feel.v
lexUnit.definition: COD: perceive, examine, or search by touch.

sentence.text: It was bulky and badly tied up with paper and string but Sarah did n't need to feel it to know what it was .
Laura leant forward , and , taking a good handful , felt the close knitting between linger and thumb .
She bent down , undid the zipper , and felt carefully inside the layers of clothing before kicking the bag to one side .
She crept stealthily along the gallery , not daring to put on a light in case she should wake Luke , past his room , feeling carefully in the half-darkness .
Having felt carefully the whole length of the injured leg , Sophie looked up .
He heard himself moan , and felt with his hands : bedclothes .
Sullivan removed one hand and felt inside his jacket , closing fingers around steel .
Jackie 's delicate fingers felt around the frame , applied a light pressure , and the window slid up about eighteen inches .
He raised himself on one elbow and gingerly felt around his feet .
Feel around in the top pocket of his blazer , there you will find the shard .
Chola stooped and felt around inside the coop for eggs .
I felt along the ledge at the top of the door and sure enough the key was there .
He deftly felt along the arm .
I was now able to breathe properly and started to feel over my body with both hands .
Feel the texture of a hand offered in greeting and try to fathom the `` Jamaican handshake , '' a ritual whose rules seem to be more complex than those of the game of cricket .
